quran[26]{c,v,t,f}:
  92,15,"where none shall burn except the most wicked,"
  92,16,"who rejected the Truth, calling it falsehood and turned his back on it."
  92,17,"But the God-fearing shall be kept away from it,"
  92,18,"the Godfearing who spends his wealth to purify himself;{1}",footnotes:1:[This does not mean that no one will enter the fire except the most wretched one]
  92,19,"not as payment for any favours that he received,"
  92,20,"but only to seek the good pleasure of his Lord Most High.{1}",footnotes:1:[This is further explanation of the sincerity of the pious man. He was not indebted in any way to the people on whom he spends his wealth so that he may be doing so in order to repay for favors received]
  92,21,"He will surely be well-pleased (with him).{1}",footnotes:1:[This verse can have two meanings and both are correct:]
  93,1,"By the bright forenoon,{1}",footnotes:1:[Here, the word duha has been used in contrast to the]
  93,2,"and by the night when it covers the world with peace:{1}",footnotes:1:[The word saja in the original does not only signify the]
  93,3,"(O Prophet), your Lord has neither forsaken you, nor is He displeased.{1}",footnotes:1:[Traditions show that revelations to the Prophet (peace]
  93,4,"Indeed what is to come will be better for you than what has gone by.{1}",footnotes:1:[This good news was given by Allah to the Prophet (peace]
  93,5,"Verily your Lord will soon give you so amply that you will be well-pleased.{1}",footnotes:1:[That is, although it will take some time, yet the time is]
  93,6,"Did He not find you an orphan and then gave you shelter?{1}",footnotes:1:[That is, there can be no question of forsaking you and]
  93,7,"Did He not find you unaware of the Right Way, and then directed you to it?{1}",footnotes:1:[The word daallan as used in the original is derived from]
  93,8,"And did He not find you in want, and then enriched you?{1}",footnotes:1:[The Prophet’s (peace be upon him) father had left only a]
  93,9,"Therefore, be not harsh with the orphan;{1}",footnotes:1:[That is, as you yourself have been an orphan and Allah]
  93,10,"and chide not him who asks,{1}",footnotes:1:[It has two meanings.]
  93,11,"and proclaim the bounty of your Lord.{1}",footnotes:1:[The word nimat (bounty) is general]
  94,1,"(O Prophet), Did We not lay open your breast{1}",footnotes:1:[To begin the discourse with this question]
  94,2,"and relieve you of the burden"
  94,3,"that had well-nigh broken your back?{1}",footnotes:1:[Some of the commentators have interpreted this to mean that before Prophethood]
  94,4,"And did We not exalt your fame?{1}",footnotes:1:[This was said at a time when no one could even conceive how the renown of the one unique individual]
  94,5,"Indeed, there is ease with hardship."
  94,6,"Most certainly, there is ease with hardship.{1}",footnotes:1:[This has been repeated twice so as to reassure the Prophet (peace be upon him) that the bad times he was passing through at that time would not last for ever]
  94,7,"So, whenever you are free, strive in devotion,"
  94,8,"and turn to your Lord with longing.{1}",footnotes:1:[So when you have finished (your duties): When you are free from other occupations]
